{"author":"Joe Oakhart","author_email":"joeoakhart+bot@navapbc.com","author_id":"594c-9dcf-5ad6-4e6d","author_sig":"{\"payload\": \"\", \"payloadType\": \"application/vnd.rebar.authorship.v1+json\", \"signatures\": [{\"keyid\": \"594c-9dcf-5ad6-4e6d\", \"sig\": \"\"}]}","data":{"body":"REBAR-DEBUG DIAGNOSIS (2026-07-21)\n\nReproduced by source scan on current origin/main: client-facing plan-review prompt bodies plan_review_E2.md, plan_review_E6.md, and plan_review_F1.md contain \"ADR 0043\"; deterministic output in det_operator_attested.py appends \"(ADR-0043)\" to suggested client remediation. Additional internal comments/docstrings contain the token but are not necessarily client-visible.\n\nRoot cause: implementation-history provenance was embedded directly in bundled reviewer instructions and one deterministic user-facing string. Those prompts are shipped into reviews of external client repositories, so the model can repeat an identifier the client cannot resolve. There is no portability contract test separating internal commentary from client-output-bearing sources.\n\nMinimal corrective seam: replace identifiers in reviewer/user-facing text with the self-contained operator-attested rule while retaining internal comments where useful. Add a scoped source contract plus deterministic-output and reviewer-output fixture tests; permit client-authored ADR citations only when grounded in the target repository.\n\nNo code changed during this diagnostic run."},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"COMMENT","timestamp":1784653335389136001,"uuid":"781e3d90-9e46-4361-aee8-8ef1568185b7"}